38. scandunt, they can clamber into the villa built out in the water, by the same entrance as the master.

neque decedit, &c., the marine villa is lost in the general idea of the impossibility of flying from care. With the whole stanza cp. 2. 16. 21 foll. and see note there. The reminiscence of Lucretius (2. 47 foll.) is more evident in this place than in that. ‘Timor et Minae’ recalls ‘metus hominum, curaeque sequaces,’ and in the following stanza we may hear the echo of ‘neque fulgorem reve· rentur ab auro, N ec clarum vestis splendorem purpureai.’

41. quodsi, &c. The application of the moral professedly to himself, really to those whose desires are not as moderate.
